MaximumTransitSpeedWater: 12kn to Sabine Pass entrance jetty then onwards to basin at 6kn. Tidal flow of 1.1kn flood and 1.6kn ebb
VisibilityRestriction: Not less than 2 Miles Visibility between the SB and the Terminal.
ArrivalSaturateVapourPressure: 70 - 115, but preferable less than 90 mbg (1.3 psig)
ManifoldArrangement: L-L/V-V-L as referenced from the stern when the bow is pointed towards the Sabine-Neches waterway’s Pass Channel
PilotBoardingLocation: At the Sea Buoy; 29°-25’ North, 93°-40’ West, or at the 29/30 buoy or anchorage.
CrewLeaveChange: Crew change and shore leave are permitted, subjectto the approval of the U.S. Coast Guard, Bureau of Customs and BorderProtection
BunkeringStoresGarbage: No bunkering. Stores allowed. Garbage collection available through agents
NoticeofReadiness: In accordance with the applicable Customer’s Agreement or applicable Other Agreement’s instructions
OtherRestrictionsRequirements: Request vessel to arrive with lines cold. Vessel may not continue in current exceeding 1kn at Buoy 34 or in channel when current exceeds 2kn
LocalCharts: US Charts required. For depths during the transit, charts can be downloaded online. http://www.swg.usace.army.mil/Missions/Navigation/HydrographicSurveys/Sabine-Neches-Waterway/
Notes:
Terminal operated by Cheniere.
Even though a conventional COU is not required, a PLA is to be signed by the Master.
Reported to contain high levels of heavier hydrocarbons C6+ which may not be included in the Certificate of Quality - potential blockage of mist separator/liquid separator and LD suction strainers particularly associated with cryogenic compressors. Refer to FN0932G Technical Fleet Notice - Heavy Hydrocarbon Effects on Cargo Equipment. If nominated for loading at this port, Masters must advise Vessel Manager and Commercial Operator.
PilotBoardingSpecificRequirement: Yes. As per Terminal Manual Rev6. Current - Transit not to commence if the cross current measured at Buoy No 34 exceeds 1.1 knots. Maneuvering not to take place if current outside the entrance to the Terminals pocket basin exceeds 1.8 knots when on ebb and 2.0 knots when on flood. Wind - LNGCs should not commence the transit to or from the Terminal during sustained winds of more than thirty (30) knots as measured at the SB Buoy and twenty-five (25) knots as measured at the SPL terminal.
BallastWater: Deballasting of untreated or un-exchanged ballast water is generally not permitted at the Terminal or anywhere else within U.S. waters.
BilgeSewage: The discharge of bilge effluents and treated or untreated sewage into the waters in and around the Terminal’s berth pocket basin is prohibited.
